Similar levels of acceptance of domestic violence for men and women in Makira Province normalize it for men and young children. Consequently, women are often blamed for being married to a violent man and are viewed as an economic burden, a status which lessens if she is divorced or dead. These local structures and norms mean that some women choose to remain in abusive relationships.
Domestic violence in the context of marriage is also intergenerational. Women who were married before Malagasy independence in 1960 were publicly “shamed” and often beaten or raped to assert the power of their new husbands. This tradition continued for many years after independence, but previously married women are now more accepting of divorce, and will get out of a violent relationship because they say it is better not to be beaten and raped.
Importance of social and family networks to support women suffering violence
Because family and community members generally condone domestic violence, some reported abuse victims turned to their husbands’ relatives and friends for help. Family and social sanctions for a domestic violence victim were severe and could include beatings, rape, and community shaming. As one man said:
“If a wife tells her husband ‘you abuse me’ then her husband will go to his friends who will ask him to beat her. If you abuse someone and they tell their husband or wife, then they’ll ask their husband to beat you.”
